<p><b>The North Nova Scotia Highlanders</b> was an <a href="/wiki/Infantry" title="Infantry">infantry</a> <a href="/wiki/Regiment" title="Regiment">regiment</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Canadian_Army" title="Canadian Army">Canadian Army</a>.</p>
<p>Founded in 1936 as The North Nova Scotia Highlanders (M.G.) by the amalgamation of the Cumberland Highlanders, The Colchester and Hants Rifles, and 'C' Company, 6th Machine-Gun Battalion, it acquired its present title in 1941. The regiment landed on Juno beach on <a href="/wiki/Normandy_Landings" title="Normandy Landings" class="mw-redirect">D-Day</a>. In 1954, as a result of the <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Report_on_the_Reserve_Army" title="Kennedy Report on the Reserve Army">Kennedy Report on the Reserve Army</a>, this regiment was amalgamated with <a href="/wiki/The_Cape_Breton_Highlanders" title="The Cape Breton Highlanders" class="mw-redirect">The Cape Breton Highlanders</a> and <a href="/wiki/The_Pictou_Highlanders" title="The Pictou Highlanders">The Pictou Highlanders</a> to form 1st Battalion <a href="/wiki/The_Nova_Scotia_Highlanders" title="The Nova Scotia Highlanders" class="mw-redirect">The Nova Scotia Highlanders</a>.</p>
<p>The North Nova Scotia Highlanders were allied to the <a href="/wiki/South_Staffordshire_Regiment" title="South Staffordshire Regiment">South Staffordshire Regiment</a> and were kitted with a blue glengarry c/w diced border, scarlet doublet, white sporran with five black points, scarlet &amp; green hose, green garter flashes with full dress only for pipers and drummers.</p>
<p>The regiment perpetuated the 25th, 106th &amp; 193rd Battalions C.E.F and held its final Order of Precedence as 34.</p>
<p>During World War 2 <a href="/wiki/Major_(rank)" title="Major (rank)" class="mw-redirect">Major</a> <a href="/wiki/Kurt_Meyer" title="Kurt Meyer">Kurt Meyer</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Waffen_SS" title="Waffen SS" class="mw-redirect">Waffen SS</a> murdered captured soldiers from the regiment.<sup id="cite_ref-Cbc2008-03-07_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cbc2008-03-07-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> After the war he was convicted, and received a life sentence. His sentence was, however commuted to five years, served in Canada.</p>
<p></p>
